					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Yeah, approximately.<br /><br />The table inside the CPU lets you choose one of these sixteen periods - <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/APU_Noise">http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/APU_Noise</a><!-- m --> - corresponding to one of sixteen sample rates between 447kHz and 440Hz.<br /><br />When used with the normal &quot;white noise&quot; mode, the effective sound is mostly a function of the sample-and-hold effect, on average it works out to your choice of corner frequency of a 1st-order lowpass (6dB/octave).<br /><br />Of course, with the tonal noise mode, the baked-in frequencies actually <em>do</em> mean things. 447kHz Ã· 93 = 4.8kHz, i.e. rate 0 on NTSC in tonal noise mode is distinctly audible as a pitch.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

